ry nature of the approach on display, articulating the way in which it draws on literary history, sociology, postcolonial studies, book history, gender studies, and media studies, among others, the book also stands as a defense of the sociology of literature as a discipline in its own right.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLiterature and society2DLC. 0aLiterature and society. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh  aauthorship.  afield theory.  aliterary studies.  apublishing.  areception.  asociology of culture.  asociology of literature.  atranslation studies.  awriters.1 aBedecarré, Madeline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLibman, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079132740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363760340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503637603423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503637603/original  a978-3-11-079132-7  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles